04611nam a22006615i 9780857455703DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574557037 a10.1515/97808574557032doi  a(DE-B1597)636859  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN345.3b.E45 2008eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.800122231 aEllen, Roy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Categorical Impulse :bEssays on the Anthropology of Classifying Behavior /cRoy Ellen. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tCHAPTER 1 Introduction: Categories, Classification and Cognitive Anthropology -- tCHAPTER 2 Anthropological Studies of Classification (1996) -- tCHAPTER 3 Classifying in its Social Context (1979) -- tCHAPTER 4 Variable Constructs in Nuaulu Zoological Classification (1975) -- tCHAPTER 5 Anatomical Classification and the Semiotics of the Body (1977) -- tCHAPTER 6 Grass, Grerb or Weed? The Ethnography of a Plant Life-form (1991) -- tCHAPTER 7 Palms and the Prototypicality of Trees (1998) -- tCHAPTER 8 The Inedible and the Uneatable (1998) -- tCHAPTER 9 Fetishism: A Cognitive Approach (1988) -- tCHAPTER 10 The Cognitive Geometry of Nature: A Contextual Approach (1996) -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClassification, as an object of recent anthropological scrutiny came to prominence during the 1960s, exemplified in the British (constructionist) tradition by the writings of Mary Douglas, and in the American ethno-semantics (cognitive) tradition by the likes of Harold Conklin and Brent Berlin. At the time, these approaches seemed by turns to contradict each other, or even to exist in parallel universes. However, over the last 30 years we have witnessed both a renewed interest in classification studies as well as a cross-fertilization of these once antagonistic approaches. These essays by one of leading scholars in this field bring together a body of influential and inter-linked work which attempts to bridge the divide between cultural and cognitive studies of classification, and which develops a more embedded and processual approach. In particular, the essays focus on people’s categorization of natural kinds as a means through which to obtain an understanding of how classifying behavior in general works, engaging with the ideas of both anthropologists and psychologists. The theoretical background is set out in an entirely new and substantial introduction, which also provides a comprehensive and systematic review of developments in cognitive and social anthropology since 1960 as these have impacted on classification studies. In short, it constitutes a useful and approachable introduction to its subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEthnologyvClassification. 0aEthnopsychologyvClassification. 0aHuman behaviorvClassification. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745570340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857455703423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857455703/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK